# Basal Ganglia Dysfunction in Parkinson's Disease: A Systematic Review

## Summary

This systematic review examines basal ganglia pathophysiology in [[parkinsons-disease]], covering the dopaminergic circuitry, neuronal loss patterns, and compensatory mechanisms in the striatum and substantia nigra.

## Key Findings

- Dopaminergic neuron loss in the substantia nigra pars compacta is the hallmark of PD
- The ventrolateral tier of the substantia nigra is most vulnerable, with 50-70% neuron loss at symptom onset
- Compensatory mechanisms (increased dopamine turnover, receptor upregulation) delay symptom onset
- Non-dopaminergic systems (noradrenergic, serotonergic, cholinergic) also degenerate in PD
- Lewy bodies containing aggregated alpha-synuclein are the pathological hallmark
- Neuromelanin-containing neurons are preferentially lost in PD
- Basal ganglia circuitry disruption produces the cardinal motor features (tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia)

## Relevance to Gut-Metal-Microbiome Axis

The selective vulnerability of neuromelanin-containing dopaminergic neurons is central to the metal axis. Neuromelanin is an [[iron]]-binding polymer that accumulates [[iron]], [[manganese]], and other metals over a lifetime. In healthy aging, neuromelanin sequesters metals safely, but in PD, neuromelanin-containing neurons release their metal cargo upon death, creating local [[iron]] and [[manganese]] overload that damages neighboring neurons ([[ferroptosis]]). This cascade depends on the total metal load reaching the substantia nigra -- which is influenced by gut [[iron]] absorption regulated by the microbiome. The [[gut-brain-axis]] delivers metals to the brain where neuromelanin concentrates them; when the system fails, the accumulated metals drive progressive neurodegeneration. Understanding basal ganglia vulnerability provides the downstream context for why gut-metal-microbiome disruption has such devastating neurological consequences.

## Limitations

- Systematic review of primarily post-mortem and imaging studies
- The relationship between Lewy body pathology and neuronal death is not fully understood
- Compensatory mechanisms make early pathology detection difficult
- Animal models do not fully recapitulate human basal ganglia pathology
